	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Agriculture Commissioner’s perspectives on the external effects of CAP reform</h1>

			
			<h4>
												06 October 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>In August 2011, an interview with EC Agriculture Commissioner Dacian Cioloş on the future financing of the CAP and its external effects was organised by <i>Afronline.org</i> (Italy) in partnership with <i>Fortune</i> (Ethiopia) and <i>Sud Quotidien</i> (Senegal), as well as newspapers in Mali and Niger. In the interview, Commissioner Cioloş stressed that while agriculture was set to fall as a proportion of the EU budget, ‘the amount effectively available for agriculture remains constant’. He emphasised the need for the EU to ‘guarantee current levels of production’, given expanding global food needs.</p><p>In terms of the external effects of the CAP, Commissioner Cioloş stressed the ‘fundamental changes’ that have occurred in the CAP, with the direct link between the level of subsidy payments and the level of production having been broken. He noted that now ‘subsidies on exported European agricultural products make up less than 0.5pc of the CAP’s budget’. Nevertheless Commissioner Cioloş highlighted the importance the EU attaches to developing smallholder farming in developing countries, both through ‘direct support to small farmers’ and through the better integration of smallholder farmers into markets.</p><p>Commissioner Cioloş rejected suggestions that SPS measures ‘represent a form of hidden protectionism’, maintaining that this is about consumer protection, with standards being applied equally to imports and domestic production.</p><p>Regarding the investment needs of the agriculture sector in Africa, Commissioner Cioloş argued that it was ‘vital to put agriculture in the centre of our development policies’. He expressed the view that ‘the world of agriculture has been put aside for too long’. However he maintained that ‘it is not Europe’s task to create the dynamics and offer a model to imitate.’ Europe is however ‘ready to support initiatives that help assert the African agricultural model.’ The Commissioner said the EU was ‘ready to support cooperation between farmers, the structuring of local markets and the development of regional agricultural policies’, which are ‘three key elements that help develop local agricultural resources based on regional and local dynamics’. Commissioner Cioloş reiterated his commitment ‘to talking regularly with my African Union counterparts’.</p><p>On financial speculation in agricultural commodity markets, Commissioner Cioloş highlighted the importance of increasing transparency in agricultural markets, promoting greater international coordination of work in this area and ensuring ‘better control of financial markets’.</p><p>On the issue of ‘land grabbing’ by foreign companies, the Commissioner took the view that ‘it is possible that large scale land investment in developing countries can at times contribute to greater productivity and efficiency of the agricultural sector, and a reduction in poverty.’ However, he also acknowledged the potential ‘negative impacts on local livelihoods, political stability, food security, equity and social cohesion, good governance and environmental sustainability’. He stressed that the CAP ‘does not encourage land deals’ and pointed out the responsibility of each government for establishing its own land policy.&nbsp;</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p><i>Fortune</i> (Addis), ‘Common approach to boosting food security’, Vol. 12, No. 590, 21 August 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://addisfortune.com/Common%20Approach%20to%20Boosting%20food%20security.htm" target="_self">http://addisfortune.com/Common%20Approach%20to%20Boosting%20food%20secur...</a></p><p><i>Sud Quotidien</i> (Dakar), ‘Les norms européennes ne sont pas rigides, ells sont strictes’, 27 August 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://www.sudonline.sn/les-normes-europeennes-ne-sont-pas-rigides-elles-sont-strictes_a_4569.html" target="_self">http://www.sudonline.sn/les-normes-europeennes-ne-sont-pas-rigides-elles...</a>&nbsp;</p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>While Commissioner Cioloş asserts that the link between levels of subsidy payments and the levels of production has been broken, the 2011 WTO trade policy review of the EU noted that in the agriculture sector the level of EU assistance to the agriculture sector ‘keeps production and exports higher , and imports lower, than would otherwise be the case’. As a consequence it was noted that after 20 years of reform, the CAP ‘continues to have negative effects both within and outside the EU’ (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Topics/WTO/Agricultural-dimensions-of-the-WTO-EU-trade-policy-review" target="_blank">Agricultural dimensions of the WTO EU trade policy review</a>’, September 2011).</p><p>Thus, according to the WTO, EU CAP policy measures continue to have external consequences. Some of these external consequences could adversely impact on ACP countries. In this context, the call from Commissioner Cioloş to ‘put agriculture in the centre of our development policies’ could be seen as a way of illustrating the Lisbon Treaty commitment to ensuring greater policy coherence.</p><p>However, it should be noted that ensuring policy coherence in large part requires ACP governments to give a clear policy lead. Issues in the dairy sector illustrate this.</p><p>In the dairy sector, any adverse impacts on ACP countries arising from the deployment of EU export refunds on milk powder make themselves felt via the purchase and production decisions of ACP dairy processing companies. Increased milk powder exports which may arise as a by-product of EU safety-net policies (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Dairy/USDA-review-of-EU-dairy-sector-development" target="_blank">USDA review of EU dairy sector development</a>’, July 2011) can adversely impact on supply arrangements between local dairy farmers and dairy processors in ACP states, reducing both prices and demand for local milk and throwing dairy development efforts into disarray.</p><p>Given that the EU maintains a cautious approach to the use of dairy export refunds and has in place a sophisticated system that allows export refund levels to be varied by destination, product and end use, potentially the use of this policy tool can be dovetailed with national dairy sector development strategies. However, this assumes the existence of a national dairy sector development strategy in the ACP country affected, and the existence of effective policy measures (import licensing arrangements and dialogue processes involving all stakeholders) to manage the import and use of milk powder.</p><p>Where such national strategies are in place, the deployment of EU dairy sector policy tools (notably export refunds) will need to be managed in ways consistent with the dairy sector development aspirations of the ACP state concerned.&nbsp;</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
	</article>

